  • A transient loss of all spinal cord activity below a spinal cord insult including flaccid paralysis, paraesthesia, loss of bladder and bowel control, loss of reflexes, priapism in males, bradycardia and hypotension.

  • Lasts around 2 weeks.

  • Possible mechanisms: Increased intra spinal cord pottassium levels;

  • release from descending tract inhibition of inhibitory neurons -> leading to inhibition of motor neurons;

  • Denervation hypersensitivity plays a role in recovery.

Mass reflex

Occurs in quadriplegic patients.
There is extreme lowering of the threshold for the withdrawal reflex. Minor stimuli can trigger disproportionate reactions like prolonged withdrawal and even flexion-extension patterns in the other limbs; Aberrant reinnervation followings spinal cord injury can cause minor stimuli to cause autonomic dysregulation (hypotension, pallor, sweating) and bladder / bowel incontinence.

Congenital adrenal hyperplasia


Congenital adrenal hyperplasia results from #autosomal-Recessive deficiency of 21-alpha hydroxylase enzyme. Deficiency diverts synthesis towards the androgenic pathway and decreases mineralocorticoid and glucocorticoid function.

  • increased testoterone -> virilization
  • Inhibition of negative feedback of ACTH results in adrenal hyperplasia.
  • Impaired aldosterone -> salt wasting.
    Other forms of CAH: 11-beta hydroxylase deff, 17-alpha hydroxylase deff and 3-beta hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase deff.

Presentation is at birth

  • females -> ambiguous genitalia
  • Males -> salt wasting crisis will be the presenting feature at < 10 days old.

Investigation: elevated 17OHP levels.

Diabetic neuropathy

Manifestations of diabetic neuropathy

pathogenesis

  • Mononeuritis is probably cause by ischemia of the vaso vasorum.
  • Diffuse neuropathy is probably caused by increased sorbitol and fructose in the Schwann cells.
  • Early stages -> demyelination -> causing decreased conduction velocity (even in the early stages) (demyelination may be reversible)
  • Progressive disease causes irreversible axonal damage.

Symmetrical distal polyneuropathy

  1. Earliest is loss of vibration sense and pain (deep before superficial) and temperature
  2. Later - loss of proprioception.
  3. Interosseous wasting of foot muscles due to neuropathy of motor nerves.
    1. High Arched food with clawing of the toes
    2. Small muscle wasting is also seen in the hands
    3. Carpal tunnel syndreme is more common in DM

Acute painful neuropathy

  1. Burning or crawling pain in the feet, shins or thighs, worse at night.
  2. Can present with IMPROVEMENT of glycaemic control but remits with continue glycaemic control
  3. Treatment: Duloxetine, TCAs, gabapentin and pregabalin are first line agents have moderate effects.

Mononeuritis and mononeuritis multiplex

  • Sudden painless palsy of any nerve.
  • However, most commonly affects CN 3 and CN 6;
  • CN 3 lesions spare the pupillary reflexes.
  • Spinal nerve roots can be affected.
  • Resolution occurs over a few months.

Diabetic amyotrophy

  • Asymmetrical Pain and weakness of the proximal leg muscles
  • Painful and tender wasting of the quadriceps muscles seen in older men with DM.
  • Usually asymmetrical.
  • Weakened / absent knee reflexes.
  • But also Extensor plantar responses +
  • CSF protein is elevated.
  • Also called lumbosacral radiculoplexus neuropathy (LRPN)
  • Pathophysiology : The most likely cause is ischemic injury from a nonsystemic microvasculitis.

Autonomic neuropathy

Usually asymptomatic but can cause significant postural hypotension.

  • Cardiovascular - loss of sinus arrhythmia, tachycardia, loss of valsalva reflex, 'denervated heart' in extreme cases
  • Gastrointestinal : vagal damage -> intractable vomiting;
    • Also dysphagia, constipation, diarrhoea (particularly at night), faecal incontinence.
    • Bacterial overgrowth in small intesting -> bile salt deconjugation, malabsorption, diarrhoea, also anaemia and macrocytosis
  • Urinary: Atonic, painless distended bladder.
  • Sexual dysfunction: Occurs in MEN and WOMEN
    • Men: Incomplete erection -> erectile failure + retrograde ejaculation.
      • Due to inadequate vascular supply, concurrent use of thiazides and beta blockers, excess alcohol

Can be precipitated by anaesthetic drugs and luteal phase of the menstrual cycle.

Anatomy of L4/L5 disk prolapse

L4/L5 disk prolapse causes compression of the L5 disk!
Source

The most prominent findings are hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and a mild nonanion-gap metabolic acidosis due to the loss of the (sodium-retaining and potassium and hydrogen ion-secreting) action of aldosterone - Source
[!TIP] Mnemonic
Mnemonic: Addisonian acidosis

  • Hypercalcemia also occurs : cause is not known.
  1. Deficient mineralocorticoids : (mineralocorticoid production may be preserved in some causes of adrenal dysfunction)
    ?Deficiency H+ secretion -> acidosis
  2. Deficient glucocorticoids : hypoglycaemia
  • predominant symptom is shock + constituional symptoms - fatigue, lethargy, N/V, abdominal pain.

Patients with chronic primary adrenal insufficiency -> symptoms and signs of (1) glucocorticoid, (2)mineralocorticoid, and, in women, (3)androgen deficiency.
In contrast, patients with secondary or tertiary adrenal insufficiency usually have normal mineralocorticoid function which is mainly stimulated by the RAAS system. Adrenal sex steroid production is also independent of pituitary action.

Causes of primary adrenal insufficiency

  • Autoimmune disease : commoner in women
  • Tuberculosis
  • rarer causes: meningogoccal septicaemia -> adrenal haemorrhage; Infiltration with malignancy or amyloid.

Management of Addisonian crisis

  • Management of addisonial crisis: 1 L within 30 to 60 minutes and large volume replacement over the next 24 hours.
  • intramuscular hydrocortison 100mg 6 hourly

Mechanism of hypotension in adrenal crisis

  • Salt wasting and dehydration
  • Glucocorticoids deficiency causes hypotension by impaired vascular responsiveness to angiotensin II and norepinephrine, prostacyclin production and renin substrate (?angiotensinogen) production.

Activated vitamin D (1,25 dihydroxyvitamin D) regulates gene transcription by binding to intracellular receptors.
Mechanism: dihydroxycholecalciferol binds to it's receptor (?nuclear receptor) and acts as a transcription regulator which increases calbindin D proteins.

This protein increases intestinal calcium absorption.
Induction of another protein in the renal tubules increases renal calcium absorption.

  • a lesser stimulation of intestinal phosphate absorption
  • Stimulation of osteoblast function and matrix calcification.
    About half of total calcium is protein unbound (mostly to albumin). The remainder ('complexed' to citrate and phosphate and 'unbound') making up the other half is the 'filtrable' part.
    PTH and activated vitamin D promote calcium re-absorption in all areas except the PCT. (DCT, TAL, Connecting tubules)
  • Glucocorticoids: Have a permissive effect on the actions of glucagon (and catecholamines) and attenuating action on insulin.

Features of dysfunction of other areas

[!INFO] Dominant hemisphere
Most often it's the left hemisphere.

#2018BSQ-OCT/Q37
Destruction of articular cartilage is a central feature. However, all other joint tissues are affected. (ligaments, tendon, synovium, menisci, subchondral bone, capsule).
Joint cells produce proinflammatory mediators (probably IL-1, IL-6 and TNF) which also stimulate the action of proteases (matrix metalloproteinases MMP) that mediate extracellular matrix destruction.

However, classic inflammation is NOT PRESENT in osteoarthritis. Synovial joint fluid only has mild leukocytosis. (but in contrast, is high in RA)

Sub chondral bone becomes sclerotic (after exposure from destruction of overlying cartilage) - there is also hypercellularity of the subchondral bone;
However, according to Robbins, OA is primarily a 'degenerative process' rather than an inflammatory one.

  • Chondrocytes responds to stress in such as way that cartilage matrix is broken down.
  • There is vertical and horizontal fibrillation and cracking of the matrix.
  • This is known as chondromalacia; the articular surface has become soft and granular (?instead of shiny and glassy)
  • Subchondral bone is then exposed and polished by friction -> bone eburnation; look like ivory! (mnemonic; 'Ebur' means ivory)
  • Pieces of bone and cartilage are disloged into the sinovial fluid - synovial 'mice'.
  • Osteophytes develop at the margin of the articular surface
  • Synovial fluid cysts occur in the subchondral bone.
  • Synovial can proliferate in severe cases to form a pannus.
  • There is subchondral bone thickening due to increased osteoblastic activity - ? sclerosis
  • Bone erosions are uncommon in OA. (? can occur in RA)

  • Limited functional impairement.
  • Fixed adduction of the thumb (squared hand) can occur with OA of the thumb.

Primary generalized OA

Associated with nodal generalized oa.
Sudden onset and severe.
Also affects hips, knee, first MTP and intervertebral joints.

  • Radiological OA may not be symptomatic and may not progress.
  • X ray doesn't show changes until late stage
  • MRI can show early cartilage changes.
  • Arthroscopy can show fissuring of the cartilage
  • Synovial fluid is viscous with leukocytes.

Rheumatoid arthritis Vs. Osteoarthritis

Distinction is important because OA management is 'palliative' while RA management is 'disease modifying'. Source<- seems reliable.

Also, in OA joints don't appear inflamed on examination; but in RA, joints are warm, soft and boggy.
